Infrastructure

Transportation

The Fort Pierce Railroad Station in the early 20th Century

Fort Pierce is strategically positioned along [US 1](/U.S._Route_1_in_Florida), a major north-south artery, and is located near its intersection with [SR 70](/Florida_State_Road_70). For those seeking faster, less scenic routes, [I-95](/Interstate_95_in_Florida) and [Florida's Turnpike](/Florida%27s_Turnpike) are conveniently accessible at the western periphery of the city. The tranquil, yet vital, [Intracoastal Waterway](/Intracoastal_Waterway) gracefully traverses through the city, offering an alternative mode of passage. For air travel, the nearest airport offering scheduled passenger service is located in [Melbourne](/Melbourne_Orlando_International_Airport), while the closest major international gateway is [Palm Beach International Airport](/Palm_Beach_International_Airport) in [West Palm Beach](/West_Palm_Beach,_Florida) [42]. The city itself, however, hosts a general aviation facility, the [Treasure Coast International Airport](/Treasure_Coast_International_Airport), catering to smaller aircraft and private flights, for those who prefer to avoid the masses.

Local transportation planning falls under the purview of the St. Lucie Transportation Planning Organization (TPO) [43]. The TPO functions as a [Metropolitan Planning Organization](/Metropolitan_planning_organization) (MPO), a federal mandate ensuring comprehensive transportation planning, programming, and the judicious allocation of State and Federal transportation funds specifically for the City of Fort Pierce. The TPO is governed by a dedicated TPO Board, composed of elected officials, representatives from the St. Lucie County School Board, and delegates from Community Transit, a division operating under The Council on Aging of St. Lucie, Inc. [44]. The genesis of the local bus system began in the 1990s as a demand-response service, initially serving only [St. Lucie County](/St._Lucie_County,_Florida). This evolved into a more structured fixed-route system, offering predetermined stops and schedules. On June 3, 2002, the [Florida Department of Transportation](/Florida_Department_of_Transportation) (FDOT) approved crucial funding, facilitating the expansion of bus service into [Martin County](/Martin_County,_Florida), at which point it was rebranded as the Treasure Coast Connector [45] [46], a rather ambitious name for a bus service.

Historically, from 1894 until 1968, the [Florida East Coast Railway](/Florida_East_Coast_Railway) provided passenger rail service to the city. Prior to a significant strike that commenced in 1963, Fort Pierce was a regular stop for several long-distance passenger trains originating from major hubs like Chicago, Cincinnati, and New York City, all en route to [Miami](/Miami). These included notable services such as the [Illinois Central Railroad](/Illinois_Central_Railroad)'s iconic [City of Miami](/City_of_Miami_(train)) and the [Louisville & Nashville Railroad](/Louisville_%26_Nashville_Railroad)'s [South Wind](/South_Wind_(train)), both embarking from Chicago. From New York, passengers could board the [Atlantic Coast Line Railroad](/Atlantic_Coast_Line_Railroad)'s [East Coast Champion](/Champion_(train)), the Havana Special, and the winter-only [Florida Special](/Florida_Special_(train)) [47] [48] [49]. Into the late 1950s, the [Dixie Flagler](/Dixie_Flagler) also offered connections to Chicago, albeit via [Atlanta](/Atlanta) [50]. Even after the strike, the FEC maintained a six-day-a-week Jacksonville-Miami train service from 1965 to 1968, a continuation enforced by court order [51]. The golden age of rail travel, much like many golden ages, eventually faded.

In more recent times, both [Amtrak](/Amtrak) and the [Florida East Coast Railway](/Florida_East_Coast_Railway) have engaged in discussions and planning for the establishment of new stations along Florida's East Coast. The cities identified by Amtrak and the Florida Department of Transportation as potential sites for these renewed services included [Stuart](/Stuart,_Florida), Fort Pierce, [Vero Beach](/Vero_Beach), [Melbourne](/Melbourne,_Florida), [Titusville](/Titusville,_Florida), [Cocoa](/Cocoa,_Florida), [Daytona Beach](/Daytona_Beach) and [St. Augustine](/St._Augustine,_Florida) [52]. However, the wheels of progress, particularly in infrastructure, tend to turn with agonizing slowness.

More recently, in 2023, [Brightline](/Brightline), the sleek [inter-city rail](/Inter-city_rail) service that currently connects [Miami](/MiamiCentral) to [Orlando](/Orlando_International_Airport_Intermodal_Terminal), announced its active search for suitable locations to establish a new station on the [Treasure Coast](/Treasure_Coast) [53]. Despite the historical presence of rail and these ongoing discussions, as of 2024, there are currently no concrete plans to add a [Brightline](/Brightline) station directly within Fort Pierce, leaving residents to ponder if modernity will ever truly arrive at their platform.

Notable people

Zora Neale Hurston's house

Fort Pierce has, like any place, been graced by the presence of individuals who, for various reasons, have managed to carve out a name for themselves. Some of these notable figures include:

Arts and entertainment

*   [Ricou Browning](/Ricou_Browning), a man of many talents, known for his stunt work, filmmaking, and acting, particularly as the iconic Gill-man in *Creature from the Black Lagoon*.
*   [Michael P. Nash](/Michael_P._Nash), a filmmaker who brought his visions to the screen.
*   [Lisa Janti](/Lisa_Janti), an actress who graced the stage and screen.
*   [A. E. Backus](/A._E._Backus), a painter whose vibrant Florida landscapes captured the essence of the region [54].
*   [Zora Neale Hurston](/Zora_Neale_Hurston), a towering figure in American literature, an influential writer, anthropologist, and folklorist whose intellect and prose continue to resonate. Her presence alone elevates the cultural cachet of Fort Pierce.
*   [Lori McNamara](/Lori_McNamara), another painter contributing to the artistic tapestry of the area [55].
*   [Ted Hewitt](/Ted_Hewitt), a country music producer, shaping the sounds of a specific genre.
*   [Gary Stewart](/Gary_Stewart_(singer)), a country singer known for his distinctive voice.

Politics

*   [Alto L. Adams](/Alto_L._Adams), who ascended to the esteemed position of Chief Justice of the [Supreme Court of Florida](/Supreme_Court_of_Florida).
*   [James E. Alderman](/James_E._Alderman), another individual who served as Chief Justice of the Florida Supreme Court, ensuring the wheels of justice, however slowly, turned.
*   [Brian Mast](/Brian_Mast), a [U.S. Representative](/U.S._Representative) who has navigated the labyrinthine halls of Washington [56].
*   [Daniel T. McCarty](/Daniel_T._McCarty), the 31st Governor of Florida [57], who held the reins of state power for a time.
*   [Allen R. Sturtevant](/Allen_R._Sturtevant), an Associate Justice of the [Vermont Supreme Court](/Vermont_Supreme_Court), proving that influence can extend far beyond Florida's borders [58].

Sports

The competitive spirit has been embodied by numerous athletes from Fort Pierce:

*   [Jeff Blackshear](/Jeff_Blackshear), an NFL guard who anchored offensive lines [59].
*   [Jamar Chaney](/Jamar_Chaney), an NFL linebacker who tackled challenges on the field [60].
*   [Yamon Figurs](/Yamon_Figurs), an NFL and CFL wide receiver, known for his speed and agility [61].
*   [Charles Johnson](/Charles_Johnson_(catcher)), an MLB catcher who commanded the diamond [62].
*   [Ladislav Karabin](/Ladislav_Karabin), a Slovak ice hockey player, bringing international talent to the list.
*   [Khalil Mack](/Khalil_Mack), an NFL linebacker, a formidable presence in professional football.
*   [Terry McGriff](/Terry_McGriff), another MLB catcher who made his mark in baseball [63].
*   [Ryan McNeil](/Ryan_McNeil_(American_football)), an NFL defensive back known for his prowess in the secondary [64].
*   [Wonder Monds](/Wonder_Monds), an NFL defensive back, whose name alone suggests a certain mystique [65].
*   [Luther Robinson](/Luther_Robinson), an NFL defensive end, a force on the defensive line [66].
*   [Larry Sanders](/Larry_Sanders_(basketball)), an NBA player, who soared on the basketball court [67].
*   [Jeff Schwarz](/Jeff_Schwarz), an MLB pitcher who toiled on the mound [68].
*   [Herbert Strong](/Herbert_Strong_(golfer)), a distinguished golfer and golf course architect, shaping both the game and its landscapes [69].
*   [LaDaris Vann](/LaDaris_Vann), a [CFL](/Canadian_Football_League) player, showcasing talent in Canadian football.

Other

And then there are those whose stories defy easy categorization, yet still left an indelible mark:

*   [Kimberly Bergalis](/Kimberly_Bergalis), tragically known as the victim of the first documented case of clinical transmission of HIV from a healthcare provider, a somber chapter in medical history.
*   [Edwin Binney](/Edwin_Binney), the co-founder of [Crayola Crayons](/Crayola) [70], who brought color into countless childhoods, a rather delightful legacy.
*   [Roslyn M. Brock](/Roslyn_M._Brock), who served as Chairman of the [National Association for the Advancement of Colored People](/National_Association_for_the_Advancement_of_Colored_People), a significant voice in the ongoing struggle for civil rights.
*   [Louise Gopher](/Louise_Gopher), celebrated as the first [Seminole](/Seminole_Tribe_of_Florida) woman to earn a bachelor's degree [71], a trailblazer for her community.
*   [John Houghtaling](/John_Houghtaling), an entrepreneur and inventor [72], whose ingenuity brought forth the "Magic Fingers" vibrating bed, a rather peculiar, yet enduring, contribution to comfort.
*   [CeeCee Lyles](/CeeCee_Lyles), a flight attendant on [United Airlines Flight 93](/United_Airlines_Flight_93) [73], whose bravery and sacrifice became a somber part of a national tragedy.

